name: Upstairs At Pier 38
description: Inspired by the rich history of Pier 38, Nico’s Upstairs is a place to gather that encompasses locally caught seafood, sourced by the renowned Honolulu Fish Auction, as well as featuring USDA Prime Steak. Our Executive Chef Drew Parker adds his own creativity to the menu by collaborating with Chef Nico Chaize, to create island cuisine using rustic French techniques. Experience our cozy lounge setting inspired by a “home away from home.” Smokey wood accents with high industrial ceilings, glowing lights, and a majestic copper bar will allow our guests to unwind with ease. Seating in the dining room is spacious, and perfect for large parties or an intimate date night. We are happy to offer a contemporary wine list with old-world treats, locally crafted beers, and captivating one-of-a-kind cocktails. Our team prefers reservations; however, walk-ins are always welcome! Join us at the Pier for enticing food, finely crafted cocktails, and a Hawaiian sunset. Parking is ample and free!

name: Ahi and Vegetable
description: With two convenient locations in Honolulu, HI, Ahi and Vegetable is the ultimate source for high-quality seafood. Whether you need to purchase wholesale seafood for an event or you're craving a quick bento, turn to Ahi and Vegetable for the freshest fish in Hawaii. At Ahi and Vegetable, they let the customer determine the menu. If you're going out with friends, you can create your own combination plate or bento comprised entirely of healthy food. If you're hosting an event, you can design a sashimi or sushi platter of any size. From fresh tuna to spicy salmon, they have everything you need to devise the perfect menu for your next event. Ahi and Vegetable is the most famous seafood restaurant downtown, and they just opened a second location at Kapalama Shopping Center. Their mission is simple: serve only the freshest fish available. They care as much about customer service as they do about the quality of their seafood, and they strive to take care of their employees.
